  "html": "\u003cdiv id=\"readability-page-1\" class=\"page\"\u003e\u003cdiv\u003e\n      \t\t\t\t\t\u003cul\u003e\n\t\t\t\t\u003cli id=\"Entry1\"\u003e\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\u003cspan\u003e\u003c/span\u003e\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\u003ca name=\"entry\" id=\"EntryAnchor\"\u003eanchor\u003c/a\u003e\n\t\t\t\t\t\n\n\t\t\t\t\t\n\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\u003cdiv\u003e\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\u003cp\u003e\u003ca href=\"https://archinect.gumlet.io/uploads/d7/d765062061b90bd03a4bd3ee57283795.jpg?auto=compress%2Cformat\" title=\"Image: pexels\" data-size=\"5472x3648\"\u003e\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\u003cimg srcset=\"https://archinect.gumlet.io/uploads/d7/d765062061b90bd03a4bd3ee57283795.jpg?fit=crop\u0026amp;auto=compress%2Cformat\u0026amp;enlarge=true\u0026amp;w=514 1x,https://archinect.gumlet.io/uploads/d7/d765062061b90bd03a4bd3ee57283795.jpg?fit=crop\u0026amp;auto=compress%2Cformat\u0026amp;enlarge=true\u0026amp;w=514\u0026amp;dpr=2 2x, https://archinect.gumlet.io/uploads/d7/d765062061b90bd03a4bd3ee57283795.jpg?fit=crop\u0026amp;auto=compress%2Cformat\u0026amp;enlarge=true\u0026amp;w=514\u0026amp;dpr=3 3x\" src=\"https://archinect.gumlet.io/uploads/d7/d765062061b90bd03a4bd3ee57283795.jpg?fit=crop\u0026amp;auto=compress%2Cformat\u0026amp;enlarge=true\u0026amp;w=514\" title=\"Image: pexels\" alt=\"Image: pexels\" width=\"514\" height=\"\"/\u003e\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\u003c/a\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003eImage: pexels\u003c/p\u003e\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\u003c/div\u003e\n\t\t\t\t\t\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\u003cdiv\u003e\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\u003cp\u003eNational nonresidential \u003ca href=\"https://archinect.com/news/tag/457129/construction-spending\" target=\"_blank\"\u003econstruction spending\u003c/a\u003e decreased 0.1% in April, according to the latest \u003ca href=\"https://archinect.com/news/tag/2138957/associated-builders-and-contractors\" target=\"_blank\"\u003eAssociated Builders and Contractors\u003c/a\u003e analysis of data published by the U.S. Census Bureau. On a seasonally adjusted annualized basis, nonresidential spending totaled $1.248 trillion.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eSpending was down on a monthly basis in 6 of the 16 nonresidential subcategories. Private nonresidential spending fell 0.5%, while public nonresidential construction spending was up 0.5% in April.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cfigure\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003ca href=\"https://archinect.gumlet.io/uploads/ea/ea6b302ff03604fc332fdc079da9036b.jpg?auto=compress%2Cformat\u0026amp;enlarge=true\u0026amp;w=1028\" data-size=\"1028x657\" target=\"_blank\"\u003e\u003cimg src=\"https://archinect.gumlet.io/uploads/ea/ea6b302ff03604fc332fdc079da9036b.jpg?auto=compress%2Cformat\u0026amp;enlarge=true\u0026amp;w=514\" srcset=\"https://archinect.gumlet.io/uploads/ea/ea6b302ff03604fc332fdc079da9036b.jpg?auto=compress%2Cformat\u0026amp;enlarge=true\u0026amp;w=514 1x,https://archinect.gumlet.io/uploads/ea/ea6b302ff03604fc332fdc079da9036b.jpg?auto=compress%2Cformat\u0026amp;enlarge=true\u0026amp;w=514\u0026amp;dpr=2 2x, https://archinect.gumlet.io/uploads/ea/ea6b302ff03604fc332fdc079da9036b.jpg?auto=compress%2Cformat\u0026amp;enlarge=true\u0026amp;w=514\u0026amp;dpr=3 3x\"/\u003e\u003c/a\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\u003cfigcaption\u003eTable credit: Associated Builders and Contractors\u003c/figcaption\u003e\u003c/figure\u003e\u003cp\u003e“Construction spending slipped in April as headwinds like trade policy uncertainty, high interest rates and tight lending standards continued to batter industrywide momentum,” said ABC Chief Economist Anirban Basu. “Nearly 22% of contractors reported tariff-related project delays or cancellations in April, and despite changes to certain import tax rates in May, policy uncertainty remains extraordinarily elevated.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cfigure\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003ca href=\"https://archinect.gumlet.io/uploads/4b/4b5ec11ab536b4e1372fb2e8190ca39a.jpg?auto=compress%2Cformat\u0026amp;enlarge=true\u0026amp;w=1028\" data-size=\"1028x645\" target=\"_blank\"\u003e\u003cimg src=\"https://archinect.gumlet.io/uploads/4b/4b5ec11ab536b4e1372fb2e8190ca39a.jpg?auto=compress%2Cformat\u0026amp;enlarge=true\u0026amp;w=514\" srcset=\"https://archinect.gumlet.io/uploads/4b/4b5ec11ab536b4e1372fb2e8190ca39a.jpg?auto=compress%2Cformat\u0026amp;enlarge=true\u0026amp;w=514 1x,https://archinect.gumlet.io/uploads/4b/4b5ec11ab536b4e1372fb2e8190ca39a.jpg?auto=compress%2Cformat\u0026amp;enlarge=true\u0026amp;w=514\u0026amp;dpr=2 2x, https://archinect.gumlet.io/uploads/4b/4b5ec11ab536b4e1372fb2e8190ca39a.jpg?auto=compress%2Cformat\u0026amp;enlarge=true\u0026amp;w=514\u0026amp;dpr=3 3x\"/\u003e\u003c/a\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\u003cfigcaption\u003eTable credit: Associated Builders and Contractors\u003c/figcaption\u003e\u003c/figure\u003e\u003cp\u003e“With the exception of data centers and certain public sector segments, the industry has few bright spots at the moment,” said Basu. “Private nonresidential spending has fallen in 3 of the first 4 months of 2025 and is on pace to decline 4% for the year. This is especially concerning given a nearly 10% year-over-year decline in computer/electronic manufacturing construction spending, the segment that bolstered the industry throughout much of 2023 and 2024.”\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eThe ABC analysis of April’s construction input price data can also be found \u003ca href=\"https://archinect.com/news/article/150481193/construction-input-prices-fall-0-1-in-april\" target=\"_blank\"\u003ehere\u003c/a\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\t\t\t\t\t\u003c/div\u003e\n\t\t\t\t\t\n\t\t\t\t\t\n\t\t\t\t\t\n\t\t\t\t\t\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\n\t\t\t\t\t\u003cbr clear=\"all\"/\u003e\n\n\t\t\t\t\t\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\u003cdiv\u003e\n\t\t\u003ch2\u003eSimilar articles on Archinect that may interest you...\u003c/h2\u003e\n\t\t\u003cul\u003e\n\t\t\t\t\t\u003cli\u003e\n\t\